[3] Diarrhea - Bangladesh (Chapainawabganj District)
Date: Fri 3 Apr 2015
Source: Dhaka Tribune [edited]
http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/apr/10/sudden-diarrhea-outbreak-sends-hundreds-hospital


A sudden outbreak of diarrhea in the Chapainawabganj municipality has put hundreds of patients in hospital, with the number increasing at an alarming rate. The outbreak was caused by bacteria in the water supply. On average 60 to 70 patients are being admitted daily at the Chapainawabganj Sadar Hospital where 450 people have already been treated in the last week. With not enough room in the hospital wards, many patients are being treated in the corridors and balconies of the hospital. The limited number of hospital staff are severely struggling to keep up with the influx of patients.

Resident physician of the Sadar hospital Shafiqul Islam said: "Most of the patients with diarrhea are from ward number 13, 14 and 15." Although the number of diarrhea patients is increasing everyday, the physicians are saying there is no reason to panic.

Chapainawabganj Civil Surgeon Dr Alauddin said: "The diarrhea is being caused by bacterial infection through the water supply of the municipality. The poly flower [as written in the original text - Mod.LL] bacteria [were] found in a water sample sent to ICDDRB [International Centre for Diarrheal Disease Research, Bangladesh] in Dhaka." He said the health department issued a cautionary public announcement in the affected areas to use boiled water and stay away from stale food, and added: "Further necessary steps will be taken once the final report of the water sample test comes out."

The municipality authority is also issuing public announcements in the affected areas to use the supplied water carefully but is yet unable to provide an alternate water supply.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Clearly the term "poly flower" does not refer to a particular bacterium but may reflect "poly" microbial "flora" as sewage contamination of a municipal water supply can, and often does, cause infections from different microbes.

Maps of Bangladesh can be seen at http://www.mapsofworld.com/bangladesh/maps/bangladesh-political-map.jpg and < https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3292841,45313>. Chapainawabganj is located on the northwestern part of Bangladesh. It is a part of the Rajshahi Division and can be seen on a map at http://www.sasnet.lu.se/sites/default/files/u4/bangmap.jpg. - Mod.LL]

